<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-371-564  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 371 564.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  June 19 1989 v10 n25 p56(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>It's MCI vs. Baby Bells in telco-freedom debate. (MCICommunications Corp.; regional Bell operating companies;information services market entry)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hackett, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US House of Representatives is holding hearings on legislationthat would allow the regional Bell operating companies (RBOCs) toenter the information services market.andP;  Washington attorney PhilipMink believes the US telecommunications industry's competitivenessis inhibited by the prohibition against the RBOCs and that USconsumers are denied access to a wealth of services, includinghome shopping and library services.andP;  On the contrary, DanielKelly, director of regulatory policy for MCI, claims the USinformation services market is already flourishing and would notbenefit much from the RBOCs' participation.andP;  Kelly further statesthat the RBOCs are in a position to undermine the quality of theircompetitors' information services, which would necessitate theFCC's implementation of costly, highly intrusive accountingmeasures.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   MCI Communications Corp. (telecommunication policy).andO;Ticker:    MCIC.andO;Topic:     Bell Regional Holding CompaniesInformation ServicesDeregulationLegislationTelecommunicationsUnited States. Congress. House.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>